Bring a large #pot{} of water to the boil and pre-heat your #grill{} to high. Slice your @spring onion{1}(sliced finely) and your @radishes{2}(sliced finely) and roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped). Peel and finely chop the @garlic{1%clove}(peeled and finely chopped).

Chop your @new potatoes{2} in half and cook them in the boiling water with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Cook until you can easily slip a knife through them. This should take around ~{10-15%minutes} depending on their size.

Place your hand flat on top of the @British chicken breasts{2} and cut in half sideways so that you have two thin slices. Now open the chicken up like a book - you've just 'butterflied' your chicken!

To make the gremolata, mix 2 tbsps of @parsley{}(chopped) with 1/2 a clove of @garlic{}(diced). Add the zest of a 1/4 of your @lemon{1}(zested) and @olive oil{1%tbsp}, @lemon juice{1%tsp} and a @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

Evenly coat each chicken breast in @olive oil{1/2%tsp} and a @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Squeeze on some lemon juice and put them on the highest shelf under the grill. Grill each side for ~{5%minutes} or until the middle is no longer pink.

Drain your new potatoes and then run them quickly under some water. Using the back of a #wooden spoon{} or something similar to break-up the potatoes slightly.

Heat @olive oil{2%tsps} in your pan on high heat and add in your potatoes. Throw in the leaves of the @rosemary{1%sprig} and a @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Cook them for a few minutes until they have gone nice and crispy around the edges.

Finally, mix your @wild rocket{1}, radishes and spring onions with @olive oil{1%tsp}. Add a @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Serve your potatoes on the side with your chicken paillard and a spoonful of gremolata. Bon appétit!